0. [COMPLETED] The git commits and the version saves on DB should be visually distinct on the "History" tab. Perhaps by different colors for the timeline bubble on the left. Moreover, the "Describe this version" textfield should be resizable in case of long messages. The Git Settings should be at the top, rather than at the bottom, otherwise one has to scroll too far. The history should cut out after let's say the 10 most recent elements (as in: not display further back). I also do not like that the button "Save Snapshot" or "Git Commit" immediately act. Incidentally, ideally the "author" in the Git settings also should persist from session to session for the user (to the last used by that user), and especially it should not - as it does now - vanish even after just navigating away briefly from the History tab.

The suggested layout and design can be found in the folder "design_history_tab". Have a look there, especially the readme file that directs you to all the relevant sources. This deserves careful study.

STATUS: Completed. Full V1 redesign implemented per design_history_tab spec:
- Git Settings accordion moved to top with collapse/expand, status summary line
- Input replaced with resizable textarea (resize: vertical)
- Two equal-weight outline buttons with icons (teal Save snapshot, rust Commit to {branch})
- 22px glyph markers: green Database for snapshots, rust GitBranch for commits, solid teal for current state
- Timeline limited to 10 most recent entries
- Author persisted via localStorage (ost_git_author key)
- Enter key no longer bypasses empty check (textarea uses newlines instead)
- Restore button only on snapshot rows (not commits)
- All existing functionality preserved (diff viewer, restore flow, feedback banners)

